{
  "text": "Since the reduction of O 2 by Ero1 oxidases produces cytotoxic H 2 O 2 in the ER, the function of ER-resident H 2 O 2 -degrading peroxidases and their crosstalk with the PDI family are likely to be fundamental (4, [CITATION_1] . For instance, the activity of peroxiredoxin IV can produce disulfides and channel them into oxidative folding [CITATION_2] . As for Ero1-derived H 2 O 2 , it will be most interesting to carry out loss-of-function analyses with two other PDI peroxidases, GPx7 and GPx8, which physically interact with Ero1a [CITATION_3] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "28372991",
